Here’s what that “PNG → CSS glyph” change actually does and why it’s better.

# Why change it?
- **Fewer requests:** you were loading two tiny PNGs (1× and 2×) via `background-image` on each bullet. Dropping them eliminates those HTTP requests (and any revalidation).  
- **Crisper at any DPI:** a text glyph scales perfectly on all displays; no blurry 1×/2× asset juggling.  
- **Smaller CSS, simpler layout:** no `background-size`, no `image-set()`, no pixel-tweaking.  
- **Theming & contrast:** a glyph inherits or can be set to your brand color/dark-mode color; easier to keep accessible.

# What actually changed
Previously (conceptually):
```css
.hero-bullets li::before {
  content: "";
  background-image: image-set(url("../media/check-24.png") 1x, url("../media/check-48.png") 2x);
  background-size: 1em 1em;
  width: 1em; height: 1em;
  /* …positioning/margins… */
}
```

Now:
```css
/* Remove the PNG background-image rule entirely */
.hero-bullets { list-style: none; }    /* we’re replacing the default bullet */
.hero-bullets li::before {
  content: "\2713";                    /* ✓ (U+2713) — safer than a literal if CSS isn’t UTF-8 */
  display: inline-grid; place-items: center;
  flex: none; width: 1em; height: 1em; line-height: 1;
  font-weight: 900;                    /* bolder tick; adjust if too heavy */
  margin-right: .5rem;                 /* space from text */
  color: #16a34a;                      /* or use currentColor / a CSS var */
  transform: translateY(.06em);        /* tiny baseline nudge */
}
```

# Accessibility & semantics
- The list remains a semantic `<ul><li>…</li></ul>` so screen readers treat it as a list.  
- The checkmark is **decorative**; pseudo-elements aren’t announced by most screen readers, which is what you want. Don’t rely on the ✓ to convey meaning by itself.

# Potential gotchas (and easy fixes)
- **Encoding:** if your CSS isn’t UTF-8, prefer `"\2713"` over a literal `✓`.  
- **Brand color / dark mode:** you can make it follow text color:
  ```css
  .hero-bullets li::before { color: currentColor; }
  .hero-bullets { color: var(--accent-600); } /* or set a token per theme */
  ```
- **Exact control over shape:** if you want a *fixed* check shape independent of fonts, use an inline SVG mask instead of a glyph (still zero network requests):
  ```css
  .hero-bullets li::before{
    content:""; display:inline-block; width:1em; height:1em; margin-right:.5rem;
    background: currentColor;
    -webkit-mask: url('data:image/svg+xml;utf8,<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16"><path fill="black" d="M6.2 11.6 2.8 8.2l1.4-1.4 2 2 5-5 1.4 1.4z"/></svg>') no-repeat center / contain;
            mask: url('data:image/svg+xml;utf8,<svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox="0 0 16 16"><path fill="black" d="M6.2 11.6 2.8 8.2l1.4-1.4 2 2 5-5 1.4 1.4z"/></svg>') no-repeat center / contain;
  }
  ```
  This keeps a consistent mark across all fonts and themes without external files.

# Net effect
- You remove two external image fetches, shave a few milliseconds off the critical path, and get scalable, themeable checkmarks that are always crisp.  
- No change needed in your HTML—this is a CSS-only swap.

If you want, I can also convert the rule to use `::marker` (native list bullet) instead of `::before`; it’s even simpler but less style-able.

