Short answer: **Yes.** You can move the GTM `<script>` **below** your stylesheet link. It will still work; you’ll just fire tags a few milliseconds later (usually fine for a content page). Keep the **`<noscript>` iframe** right after `<body>` unchanged, and keep your **theme boot script** where it is (so you don’t get a flash of wrong theme).

Here’s the precise patch for your current `index.html`:

## 1) Keep preconnect early (and make it effective)
Change this (in `<head>`):
```html
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://www.googletagmanager.com">
```
to:
```html
<link rel="preconnect" href="https://www.googletagmanager.com" crossorigin>
```

## 2) Move the GTM snippet below the CSS link
**Find this block (currently near the top of `<head>`):**
```html
<!-- Google Tag Manager -->
<script>(function (w, d, s, l, i) {
  w[l] = w[l] || []; w[l].push({'gtm.start': new Date().getTime(), event: 'gtm.js'});
  var f = d.getElementsByTagName(s)[0], j = d.createElement(s),
      dl = l != 'dataLayer' ? '&l=' + l : '';
  j.async = true;
  j.src = 'https://www.googletagmanager.com/gtm.js?id=' + i + dl;
  f.parentNode.insertBefore(j, f);
})(window, document, 'script', 'dataLayer', 'GTM-KKDQNKRP');</script>
<!-- End Google Tag Manager -->
```

**Cut it** from there and **paste it immediately after** your stylesheet line:
```html
<link rel="stylesheet" href="assets/css/tuition-css-1.0.0.css?v=1.0.4.D" />

<!-- Google Tag Manager -->
<script>(function (w, d, s, l, i) {
  w[l] = w[l] || []; w[l].push({'gtm.start': new Date().getTime(), event: 'gtm.js'});
  var f = d.getElementsByTagName(s)[0], j = d.createElement(s),
      dl = l != 'dataLayer' ? '&l=' + l : '';
  j.async = true;
  j.src = 'https://www.googletagmanager.com/gtm.js?id=' + i + dl;
  f.parentNode.insertBefore(j, f);
})(window, document, 'script', 'dataLayer', 'GTM-KKDQNKRP');</script>
<!-- End Google Tag Manager -->
```

## 3) Don’t touch the `<noscript>` block
Leave this where it already is—right after `<body>`:
```html
<!-- Google Tag Manager (noscript) -->
<noscript><iframe src="https://www.googletagmanager.com/ns.html?id=GTM-KKDQNKRP"
  height="0" width="0" style="display:none;visibility:hidden"></iframe></noscript>
<!-- End Google Tag Manager (noscript) -->
```

### Trade-offs / gotchas (so you’re not surprised)
- **Measurement timing:** You may slightly delay the first GTM “container loaded” event. If you have tags that must run *before* anything else (e.g., Consent Initialization), ensure you don’t run other third-party scripts earlier than GTM. On your page, that’s not an issue.
- **Performance:** Moving the inline GTM code below the CSS link reduces main-thread work at the very start and keeps your CSS parsing prioritized. With the `preconnect` in place, the socket to GTM is still warmed early.
- **Safer alternative (optional):** If you want to go further, you can delay GTM to `load`/`requestIdleCallback`—but you’ll miss some immediate pageviews. Your current plan (just moving it below CSS) is the pragmatic middle ground.

If you want, I can produce a small diff of your actual file with these edits applied.
